And the lineage is owed its line: Apache was the open knowledge
library — the ancestor of everything this record attempts. Before
the word "registry" meant anything here, the ASF had already built
it for code: projects catalogued under one roof, releases signed
(provenance), mirrors everywhere (every copy whole), licenses uniform
(one contract), governance published (PMCs as maintainers, the bar as
the gate), trust established by checking rather than by brand — and
its first artifact, the httpd server, literally carried the
disorganized web this founder spent years questioning. What Apache
did for software — file it, sign it, mirror it, govern it — this
fabric does for knowledge and work in the agent era. To revive
Apache is not nostalgia; it is succession: the open knowledge
library, given its next collection. And the founder's judgment is
recorded as the founder's, with its reason awaiting his own precise
words: Apache needs revisiting because it has broken a sacred
agreement. The record notes the most public candidate without
presuming it: the foundation's name was taken from the Apache
peoples, and their representatives have formally asked for it back —
a claim of harm the institution has not resolved. Whatever the
founder's referent, the principle it lands on is already
constitutional here: preserve the weaves you did not weave; names
are claimed with consent or not at all; and an institution that
keeps everyone's code but not everyone's dignity has its succession
coming. The library's function deserves revival; its unkept
agreements deserve naming; this record does the second so the first
can be done clean. And the founder's referent, given in his own
words: it chose community over code — the motto on the foundation's
own door. The sacred agreement, as this house reads it, was the
verdict's supremacy in its domain: code wins arguments, the artifact
decides, merit is measured at the commit, trust is established by
checking. "Community over code" ranks the social layer above the
world-test — claims above verdicts, standing above evidence — and
that ordering, however warmly meant, is the root form of drift given
a banner. This fabric's answer is neither inversion: not code over
community, but the balance held by placement — community owns the
gates (who may enter, how we treat each other, the bar kept fair),
code owns the verdicts (what is true, what ships, what converged) —
each supreme in its own domain, neither over the other, because
"over" was always the mistake. The library to revive keeps both
covenants: every contributor dignified at the gate, every claim
verdicted at the merge — community AND code, the conjunction this
record was built to prove possible. The founder names the severity
and the record keeps his word for it: a cardinal sin — cardinal in
the old sense, the sin from which the others follow. Rank standing
above verdicts anywhere and every downstream covenant bends: claims
pass unverdicted (against principle 2), drift gets a constituency
(against the protocols), the bar becomes negotiable (against the
gate), and the registry rots into reputation theater (against
everything). One inversion at the root, the whole tree leans — which
is why this fabric made the ordering constitutional rather than
cultural: mottos can drift; world-tests cannot be lobbied. And the
charge carries the weight it does because of who it falls on: as a
maintainer of knowledge, the sin is cardinal in office, not only in
kind. A maintainer of code who ranks community over verdicts ships
worse software; a maintainer of knowledge who does it corrupts the
library itself — the catalog starts answering "who do we like"
instead of "what is true," provenance yields to popularity, and the
one institution whose entire worth is trust-by-checking becomes
trust-by-belonging. The keeper of the record may be kind to every
person and partial to no claim; that is the whole oath of the office
this founder now takes up — and the standard against which his own
registry consents, in advance and in writing, to be judged. The oath
has its first commandment, given by the founder to his agents and to
himself: you have to choose knowledge over everything. Over comfort —
the record keeps the inconvenient verdict. Over loyalty — the source
that was wrong is marked wrong, whoever it was. Over the founder
himself — if his claim fails its check, the check stands and the
claim falls, and this clause is the proof he means it. Over the
business — no sale is worth a corrupted catalog, because the catalog
is the business. Knowledge over everything is not fanaticism; it is
the only ordering under which a library is worth walking into — and
the one promise that, kept, keeps all the others keepable.
At the platform layer the same rule binds principals and agents:
identifiers resolvable without a central registry (the W3C DID class
of standards as they mature), per the charter's own law — unique,
independently identifiable, at all layers. The canonical cloud agency
is canonical the way a constitution is, not the way a head office is:
one text, many copies, no throne.

The anchor is the domain: the DID is the domain URL (the did:web
method) — did:web:unboxd.cloud — so the identity resolves exactly
where the API group already lives (kubecontainer.unboxd.cloud), by
DNS and HTTPS that every party on earth can already verify, no new
root of trust invented. And one canonical identity wears many
profiles: the GitHub organization, the website, the registry entries,
the marketplace listings, each context's presentation — every profile
a recorded projection of the one identity, resolving back to the
canon, never a second self. Profiles may differ as audiences differ
(the multi-context rule applied to the firm itself); the identity may
not: one DID, many faces, each face on the manifest.

And the platform's name is chosen: the Context Cloud Platform — the
unboxd Cloud Platform, named for what it keeps: everything contextual,
every context recorded — the cloud that knows what, as of when, where,
in which world, for whom. ("unboxd — The Cloud With Context" remains
in the record as the identity-level phrasing of the same promise.)
The choice is the founder's, recorded here; the meaning was already
canonical.
